        "title": "What methods and properties are available in Java array like String[] strs?",
        "body": "<p>I could not locate the package in which Java defines raw arrays like String[] strs\n( not ArrayList). <\/p>\n\n<p>What methods and properties are defined in such Java array and how do I return an iterator for such array supposed I am asked to return an iterator for two integers begin and end?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 8302132,
        "tags": ["java"],
        "score": 6,
        "accepted_answer_id": 8302221,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 6147
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/9a9793fdeb3b94e185c8c99c0238372f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 184870,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 421195,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/421195/paulsm4",
                "reputation": 122849,
                "display_name": "paulsm4",
                "accept_rate": 83
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 5,
            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1488980809,
            "creation_date": 1322513916,
            "body": "<p>Here's a good summary:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p><a href=\"https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-10.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">https://docs.oracle.com/javase/specs/jls/se7/html/jls-10.html<\/a><\/p>\n  \n  <p>10.7 Array Members <\/p>\n  \n  <p>The members of an array type are all of the following:<\/p>\n  \n  <ul>\n  <li><p>The public final field length, which contains the number of components of the array (length may be positive or zero)<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>The public method clone, which overrides the method of the same name in class Object and throws no checked exceptions<\/p><\/li>\n  <li><p>All the members inherited from class Object; the only method of Object that is not inherited is its clone method<\/p><\/li>\n  <\/ul>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>As far as \"iterators\"; the \"beginning\" and \"end\" are simply \"0\" and \".length - 1\".  You can always implement your own class that wraps an array and implements <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.5.0/docs/api/java/util/Iterator.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Iterator<\/a>.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8302221,
            "question_id": 8302132,
            "last_edit_date": 1488980809
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/5b11ea95357e9daba7e3eb37ebf720c0?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 390844,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 751158,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/751158/ziesemer",
                "reputation": 28897,
                "display_name": "ziesemer",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1322513978,
            "creation_date": 1322513621,
            "body": "<p>The only properties available (specific to Arrays) are really <code>.length<\/code>, and the index accessor, e.g. <code>[0]<\/code>.<\/p>\n\n<p>Arrays can be used in the new for loop syntax provided with Java 1.5:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>for(String s : new String[]{\"a\", \"b\", \"c\"}){\n  // Something with s.\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>You can also access an Array as a List, using <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#asList%28T...%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#asList%28T...%29<\/a> .<\/p>\n\n<p>Also see the rest of the <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/index.html?java/util/Arrays.html\" rel=\"nofollow\">Arrays<\/a> class for many other operations that exist to operate specifically on arrays.  (Here, we have a class that operates <em>on<\/em> arrays, rather than the array containing all of the useful properties and methods.)<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 8302174,
            "question_id": 8302132,
            "last_edit_date": 1322513978
        }
